answerText: Octahedral molecular geometry[10] This kind of molecular geometry describes a central atom that is bonded to four other atoms, while also possessing one lone pair of electrons. An example is sulfur tetrafluoride.

question: Question: For 10 points each, give some molecular geometries you learned aboutor didn't learn about in inorganic chemistry: [10] This kind of molecular geometry sees a central atom bonded to six other atoms.  It includes compounds like sulfur hexafluoride, and cubes have this kind of symmetry.
